e populated it.","impact":"Pre-start stakers can be erased from the baseline pool accounting used to seed later epochs. If epoch 1 and subsequent epochs are still initialized lazily, an attacker can propagate the forged zero snapshot forward and distort or deny the initial reward allocation for legitimate stakers.","paths":["Users deposit before epoch 1 starts, so epoch 0 is initialized and `poolSize[token][0]` becomes nonzero.","An attacker later calls `manualEpochInit([token], 0)`, which overwrites that existing snapshot with zero.","Before any real interaction repairs the chain, the attacker or anyone else initializes later epochs from the forged predecessor, propagating the zero baseline into live reward epochs."],"round":5,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-013","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Permissionless `getInterest()` can confiscate unrelated stablecoins held by the contract","locations":["Staking.sol:332","Staking.sol:340","Staking.sol:342","Staking.sol:344","Staking.sol:349"],"claim":"`getInterest()` redeems all cTokens for a stablecoin and then treats every on-contract token balance above `stableCoinBalances[token]` as team-owned interest. The function does not distinguish real Compound yield from unrelated stablecoins already sitting on the contract, such as accidental direct transfers or principal stranded on the contract by earlier accounting mismatches, as long as some cToken balance exists to satisfy the function's entry check.","impact":"Stablecoins that do not belong to the team can be irreversibly transferred to `TEAM_ADDRESS` by any caller. This turns stray transfers or previously stranded principal into permanent loss of funds for their rightful owner.","paths":["Stablecoins end up on the staking contract without increasing `stableCoinBalances[token]`, while the contract still holds some corresponding cTokens.","Any account calls `getInterest(token)`, which redeems all cTokens for that market.","The function computes `interest = IERC20(token).balanceOf(address(this)) - stableCoinBalances[token]` and transfers that full difference to `TEAM_ADDRESS`, including unrelated funds."],"round":5,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-014","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Unexpected cToken transfers are misclassified as protocol yield and can be swept to the team","locations":["Staking.sol:286","Staking.sol:314","Staking.sol:318","Staking.sol:336","Staking.sol:344"],"claim":"The interest-handling logic treats the contract's entire Compound position as if it were backed by tracked user principal. If anyone transfers `cUSDC`, `cUSDT`, or `cDAI` directly to the staking contract, `balanceOfUnderlying(address(this))` and later redeemed underlying increase while `stableCoinBalances[token]` does not, so the surplus is classified as withdrawable 'interest' and can be redeemed and forwarded to `TEAM_ADDRESS`.","impact":"Accidentally or intentionally transferred cTokens are confiscatable. Any caller can trigger `getInterestFromCompound()` to redeem most of their underlying value to the team, and `getInterest()` can ultimately sweep the remainder as well. This broadens the asset-confiscation surface beyond raw stablecoins already sitting in the contract wallet.","paths":["A third party transfers `cUSDC`, `cUSDT`, or `cDAI` directly to the staking contract.","`stableCoinBalances[token]` stays unchanged, but the contract's Compound position and its underlying value rise.","Any caller invokes `getInterestFromCompound(token)` or `getInterest(token)`.","The donated cToken position is treated as excess yield and its underlying is sent to `TEAM_ADDRESS`."],"round":6,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-015","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Withdrawal checkpoint math lets users keep late deposits with inflated same-epoch weight","locations":["Staking.sol:186","Staking.sol:192","Staking.sol:430","Staking.sol:443","Staking.sol:448"],"claim":"The checkpoint model collapses all same-epoch deposits into one `newDeposits` bucket with a single averaged `multiplier`, and `withdraw()` never tracks which tranche is actually being removed. If a user makes multiple deposits in the same epoch, withdrawing an earlier high-weight tranche only reduces `newDeposits` while preserving the averaged multiplier on the remainder. If a user starts the epoch with carried balance and then deposits late, withdrawing at least `newDeposits` moves the remainder into `startBalance` with `BASE_MULTIPLIER`, which can leave only the late deposit recorded as full-epoch stake.","impact":"A user can overstate their effective balance for the current epoch and capture more than their fair share of epoch rewards at the expense of honest stakers. Because this only requires timing deposits and withdrawals around the epoch boundary, it is a repeatable economic-extraction vector rather than a one-off accounting glitch.","paths":["Deposit a large amount early in an epoch, deposit a smaller amount near the epoch end, then withdraw the early deposit before rollover; the remaining late deposit keeps the blended multiplier instead of its true near-zero weight.","Begin the epoch with an existing carried balance, add a large deposit near the epoch end, then withdraw an amount equal to or larger than `newDeposits`; the code converts the remainder to `startBalance` with `BASE_MULTIPLIER`, so only the late deposit can remain while being credited as full-epoch stake."],"round":7,"source_agents":["codex"]}],"rejected_candidates":[{"title":"Any dust withdrawal can indefinitely block emergency exits for an entire token","source_agents":["codex"],"reason":"Merged into updated finding `F-001`; this round materially broadened the existing zero-amount griefing issue to include tiny positive withdrawals because the timer is global per token."}]}
